            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <p>At Ptolemais there are three similar bases for members of the Lagid family (<ref type="inscription">igcyr033700</ref>, <ref type="inscription">igcyr033800</ref> and 
                    <ref type="inscription">igcyr084300</ref>), which were re-used in the same Roman monument that seems to lay upon the foundations of a Hellenistic monumental base to which 
                    they probably all belonged, perhaps along with a fourth one, now lost. The Roman monument is part of the so-called Square of the Cisterns, which may have been formerly either 
                    the gymnasium (Stucchi's opinion) or the agora (Laronde's opinion).</p>
                <p>The present dedication may have been erected earlier than the two others, which, as Criscuolo established, were modelled on it between 168 and 164 B.C. 
	               in order to form a monumental base. However, the lettering does not show a span of time as long as one century (Arsinoe died in 270).</p>
                <p> It is not clear whether the city mentioned at l. 3  might have been still Barka and not yet Ptolemais, for the cult of Arsinoe was specially developed in harbours and not 
	               necessarily in the city-centre; however, as we now know that Ptolemais was founded probably after 260 (Laronde) and certainly before 251 (Mueller), it is highly plausible 
	               that the dedication to Arsinoe was erected by the city of Ptolemais in a prominent place.</p>
                <p/>
            </div>
